sec.p:
The Monte Carlo Dropout (MC Dropout) method was applied for quantifying prediction uncertainty. After training, each test image was passed through the model 50 times with dropout enabled during inference, producing a distribution of stochastic outputs. The mean of the predicted probabilities from these forward passes was used as the final classification output:
\begin{equation*}
\mathbb{E}_{q\left(y^{*} \mid x^{*}\right)}\left(y^{*}\right) \approx \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^{T} \hat{y}^{*}\left(x^{*}, W_{1}^{(t)}, \ldots, W_{L}^{(t)}\right)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
where $\mathbb{E}_{q\left(y^{*} \mid x^{*}\right)}\left(y^{*}\right)$ is the expected prediction for the input $x^{*}$ under the predictive distribution $q\left(y^{*} \mid x^{*}\right)$, representing the mean prediction, $T$ is the number of stochastic forward passes through the model, $\hat{y}^{*}\left(x^{*}, \mathbf{W}_{1}^{(t)}, \ldots, \mathbf{W}_{L}^{(t)}\right)$ is the model's predicted output during the $t$-th pass, given input $x^{*}$ and a specific set of sampled weights.

The standard deviation of predictions across forward passes served as a measure of uncertainty:
\begin{equation*}
\operatorname{Var}\left(y^{*}\right) \approx \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^{T}\left(\hat{y}_{t}^{*}\right)^{2}-\left(\frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^{T} \hat{y}_{t}^{*}\right)^{2}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
where $\operatorname{Var}(y)$ represents the predictive variance of the model for a new input $x$, quantifying the uncertainty in its predictions, and $\hat{y}_{t}^{*}$ corresponds to the scalar prediction generated at each pass.

Gradient-weighted Class Activation Mapping (GradCAM), a post-hoc visualization method widely used for explaining the spatial reasoning of CNNs, was deployed for generating interpretations of the model's predictions [12]. Grad-CAM identifies the spatial regions of an input image that contribute most significantly to a model's decision, offering visual explanations without requiring architectural modifications or retraining. The method operates by computing the gradients of the predicted class score $y^{c}$ with respect to the feature maps $A^{k}$ from a chosen network layer. These gradients are then globally averaged to produce importance weights $\alpha_{k}^{c}$ for class $c$ and channel $k$:
\begin{equation*}
\alpha_{k}^{c}=\frac{1}{Z} \sum_{i} \sum_{j} \frac{\partial y^{c}}{\partial A_{i j}^{k}}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
where $Z$ is the number of spatial locations. The final GradCAM heatmap is computed by taking a weighted combination of the feature maps, followed by a ReLU activation:
\begin{equation*}
L_{\text{Grad}-\text{CAM}}^{c}=\operatorname{ReLU}\left(\sum_{k} \alpha_{k}^{c} A^{k}\right)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
